content.text:
To add an edit option and dynamic scrolling to the "Recent Sales" section in your HTML file, you can follow these steps:

### 1. Add Edit Button to Each Sale Record

First, you need to add an "Edit" button to each sale record in the "Recent Sales" section. This button will allow users to edit the details of a sale.

Modify the `loadSalesRecords` function to include an "Edit" button:

```html
<div id="sales-records"></div>
```

Update the JavaScript function:

```javascript
function loadSalesRecords() {
    const container = document.getElementById('sales-records');
    const countElement = document.getElementById('sales-count');
    const summaryDiv = document.getElementById('sales-summary');
    countElement.textContent = salesData.length;
    if (salesData.length === 0) {
        container.innerHTML = '<div class="no-data">No sales records yet. Add your first sale above!</div>';
        summaryDiv.style.display = 'none';
        return;
    }

    // Update summary
    const totalSales = salesData.length;
    const totalCost = salesData.reduce((sum, sale) => sum + sale.costPrice, 0);
    const totalSelling = salesData.reduce((sum, sale) => sum + sale.sellingPrice, 0);
    const totalProfit = salesData.reduce((sum, sale) => sum + sale.profit, 0);
    document.getElementById('summary-total-sales').textContent = totalSales;
    document.getElementById('summary-total-cost').textContent = `‚Çπ${totalCost.toFixed(2)}`;
    document.getElementById('summary-total-selling').textContent = `‚Çπ${totalSelling.toFixed(2)}`;
    document.getElementById('summary-total-profit').textContent = `‚Çπ${totalProfit.toFixed(2)}`;
    summaryDiv.style.display = 'block';

    const recentSales = salesData.slice(-10).reverse();
    container.innerHTML = recentSales.map(sale => `
        <div class="sales-item">
            <button class="delete-btn" onclick="deleteSale(${sale.id})">üóëÔ∏è</button>
            <button class="edit-btn" onclick="editSale(${sale.id})">‚úèÔ∏è</button>
            <h4>${sale.itemName}</h4>
            <p><strong>Category:</strong> ${sale.category}</p>
            <p><strong>Customer:</strong> ${sale.customerName}</p>
            <p><strong>Phone:</strong> ${sale.customerPhone}</p>
            ${sale.customerAddress && sale.customerAddress !== 'Not provided' ? `<p><strong>Address:</strong> ${sale.customerAddress}</p>` : ''}
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> ${new Date(sale.saleDate).toLocaleDateString()}</p>
            <p><strong>Cost:</strong> ‚Çπ${sale.costPrice.toFixed(2)}</p>
            <p><strong>Selling Price:</strong> ‚Çπ${sale.sellingPrice.toFixed(2)}</p>
            <p style="color: ${sale.profit >= 0 ? '#4ecdc4' : '#ff6b6b'}; font-weight: bold;">
                <strong>Profit:</strong> ‚Çπ${sale.profit.toFixed(2)}
            </p>
        </div>
    `).join('');
}
```

### 2. Implement the Edit Functionality

Add a function to handle the editing of a sale record:

```javascript
function editSale(id) {
    const sale = salesData.find(sale => sale.id === id);
    if (!sale) return;

    // Populate the form with the sale data
    document.getElementById('itemName').value = sale.itemName;
    document.getElementById('category').value = sale.category;
    document.getElementById('costPrice').value = sale.costPrice;
    document.getElementById('sellingPrice').value = sale.sellingPrice;
    document.getElementById('saleDate').value = sale.saleDate;
    document.getElementById('customerName').value = sale.customerName;
    document.getElementById('customerPhone').value = sale.customerPhone;
    document.getElementById('customerAddress').value = sale.customerAddress;

    // Remove the sale from the list
    salesData = salesData.filter(sale => sale.id !== id);
    localStorage.setItem('jewelrySales', JSON.stringify(salesData));
    loadSalesRecords();
}
```

### 3. Add Dynamic Scrolling

To enable dynamic scrolling, you can set a fixed height for the sales records container and enable overflow scrolling:

```css
#sales-records {
    max-height: 400px; /* Adjust height as needed */
    overflow-y: auto;
}
```

### 4. Update HTML and CSS

Ensure your HTML and CSS are updated to reflect these changes. The CSS for the edit button can be similar to the delete button:

```css
.edit-btn {
    background: #4ecdc4;
    color: white;
    border: none;
    padding: 8px 12px;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: 12px;
    position: absolute;
    top: 10px;
    right: 50px; /* Adjust position as needed */
}

.edit-btn:hover {
    background: #3bb3a1;
}
```

With these changes, you should have an edit option for each sale record and dynamic scrolling for the "Recent Sales" section.
